response:
 During the first year, ABC's stock price starts at $ \$100 and increases $ 100\% $. What is the price of the stock, in dollars, at the end of the first year? </think>
\begin{align*}
\text{Price after increase} &= \text{Starting price} + \text{Price * Increase} \\
&= \$100 + \$100 \times 100\% \\
&= \$100 + \$100 \\
&= \$200
\end{align*}

During the second year, its stock price goes down $ 25\% $ from its price at the end of the first year. What is the price of the stock, in dollars, at the end of the second year? </think>
\begin{align*}
\text{Price decrease} &= \text{Price at the end of the first year} \times \text{Decrease} \\
&= \$200 \times 25\% \\
&= \$200 \times 0.25 \\
&= \$50
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
\text{Price at the end of second year} &= \text{Price at the end of the first year} - \text{Price decrease} \\
&= \$200 - \$50 \\
&= \$150
\end{align*}
